                        <div class="destination-common-title">
                            <h4>More Details:</h4>
                        </div>
                        <p>
                            The weekly souks of Taza typically take place once a week, and their specific day may vary from one locality to another. These souks attract residents from the surrounding areas, as well as farmers, herders, and artisans from the region. They provide a unique opportunity for both residents and visitors to come together, exchange goods, and socialize.

                            The Taza souk is divided into different sections, each dedicated to a specific type of product or activity. Here are some examples of typical sections that can be found in a weekly souk in Taza:
                          <ol>
                                <li> <strong style="color:orangered">Livestock market:</strong> This is one of the most significant parts of the souk, where farmers and herders come to buy and sell animals such as sheep, cows, goats, and chickens.</li>
                                <br/>
                                <li> <strong style ="color:orangered">Fruits and vegetables market:</strong> This section is filled with colorful stalls offering a variety of fresh and local produce, ranging from juicy fruits to flavorful vegetables.</li>
                                <br />
                                <li>
                                    <strong style="color:orangered">Artisan market:</strong> Here, one can find traditional Moroccan handicrafts, including carpets, pottery, jewelry, clothing, and many other handmade items.
                                </li>
                                <br />
                                <li> <strong style="color:orangered">Food market: </strong>This is where visitors can indulge in a variety of delicious Moroccan dishes and traditional snacks. Stands often offer skewers, freshly baked bread, pastries, and refreshing beverages.</li>
                                <br />
                            </ol>

                            The weekly souks of Taza are lively, bustling, and full of life. They present a unique opportunity to immerse oneself in the local culture, meet warm-hearted locals, and savor delicious Moroccan cuisine. Bargaining is also a common practice in these souks, so it is advisable to negotiate prices before making a purchase.
                        </p>
